Free Solutions
1. MediaPipe (Google)
Pros:

Price: Completely free and open-source
Performance: Optimized for real-time processing, <100ms latency
Bone tracking: Full 21-keypoint hand skeleton model
Cross-platform: Native support for Windows, macOS, iOS, Android
Accuracy: 95.7% palm detection precision
GPU acceleration: TensorFlow Lite GPU inference
Documentation: Excellent documentation and community support
Cons:

Setup complexity: Requires C++/Python knowledge for advanced customization
Model size: ~10MB model download
Limited gestures: Built-in gesture recognition is basic

2. OpenPose (CMU)
Pros:

Price: Free and open-source
Bone tracking: 2x21 hand keypoints (42 total points)
Established: Well-tested academic solution
Multi-person: Can track multiple hands simultaneously
Accuracy: High precision for research applications
Cons:

Performance: Heavy computational requirements, may exceed 0.5s latency
Cross-platform: Limited mobile support (primarily desktop)
Setup: Complex installation and dependencies
Real-time: Not optimized for real-time applications
Hardware: Requires powerful GPU for acceptable performance

3. HandsFree.js
Pros:

Price: Free and open-source
Easy integration: Simple JavaScript API
Cross-platform: Runs in any modern web browser
Setup: Minimal setup required
MediaPipe backend: Uses proven MediaPipe technology
Cons:

Web-only: Limited to web browser environments
Performance: JavaScript overhead, may not meet <0.5s requirement
Mobile limitations: Inconsistent mobile browser performance
Features: Less comprehensive than native implementations

4. Unity XR Hands (Unity Technologies)
Pros:

Price: Free with Unity (included in Unity engine)
Integration: Native Unity integration with seamless workflow
Cross-platform: Supports Windows, macOS through OpenXR providers
Bone tracking: Full hand joint tracking with XRHandJoint structs
Custom gestures: Built-in gesture authoring tools for dynamic gestures
Performance: Optimized for real-time Unity applications
Documentation: Comprehensive Unity documentation and samples
OpenXR standard: Uses industry-standard OpenXR API
Cons:

Unity dependency: Requires Unity engine (not standalone)
Limited mobile: No direct iOS/Android support without XR hardware
Provider dependent: Requires OpenXR-compatible hardware/software
XR focused: Primarily designed for VR/AR headsets, not standard cameras
Hardware requirement: Needs compatible XR devices (Meta Quest, HoloLens, etc.)
Learning curve: Requires Unity XR development knowledge

Paid Solutions
1. Ultraleap (Leap Motion)
Pros:

Performance: Ultra-low latency (~20ms)
Bone tracking: Full finger bone model with 4 bones per finger
Accuracy: Specialized infrared sensors provide high precision
Cross-platform: Windows, macOS, Android support
SDK: Mature C API (LeapC) with good documentation
Cons:

Price: ~$100+ for hardware device
Hardware dependency: Requires specialized Ultraleap controller
Limited mobility: Tethered to hardware device
iOS: No native iOS support
Range: Limited tracking range (8cm above device)
2. ManoMotion SDK
Pros:

Performance: Optimized for mobile devices
Cross-platform: iOS and Android support
No hardware: Camera-only solution
Gesture recognition: Built-in advanced gesture classification
Commercial support: Professional customer support
Cons:

Price: Contact-based pricing (estimated $500-2000+/year)
Limited platforms: No Windows/macOS desktop support
Closed source: Proprietary solution
Documentation: Limited public documentation
Licensing: Complex commercial licensing terms
3. Nuitrack SDK
Pros:

Price: $49.99/year per sensor - most affordable paid option
Cross-platform: Windows, macOS, Linux, iOS, Android
Multiple sensors: Supports 30+ depth sensor types
Full body: Complete skeleton tracking including hands
Performance: Two tracking engines (fast "Classical" and "AI")
Cons:

Depth sensor required: Needs additional hardware (Kinect, RealSense, etc.)
Hand detail: Less detailed than hand-specific solutions
Setup complexity: Requires depth sensor setup and calibration
Annual licensing: Recurring cost per deployment
Limited hand gestures: Focus on body tracking, not fine hand gestures
Recommendation
For your requirements (dynamic gestures, UI control, <0.5s latency, cross-platform, on-device), MediaPipe remains the optimal choice. It offers the best balance of performance, cost, and cross-platform compatibility while providing full bone tracking capabilities.

Additional considerations:
- Unity XR Hands: Excellent if you're building in Unity and targeting XR/VR platforms, but requires XR hardware rather than standard cameras
- Ultraleap: Best performance option if you can accept hardware dependency and higher costs